         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">9/4/95. ¶  ¶ There is a sort of moral obligation, dear Sir Joseph, to point out errors, even if trifling, in your great Kew-Index. Acacia tortilis is not in the 9th but in the 10th vol. Hayne figured....</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">95.04.09</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Letters to Joseph Hooker, vol. 16, f. 18.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">9/4/95.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>There is a sort of moral obligation, dear Sir Joseph, to point out errors, even if trifling, in your great Kew-Index. <name key="Acacia%20tortilis">Acacia tortilis</name> is not in the 9th but in the 10th vol. Hayne figured.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M is correcting the entry in <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Index kewensis</seg> (B. Jackson (1895)), vol. 1, p. 13 (issued 1893); Hayne (1805-37), vol. 10, tab. 31.</p>
               </note> Are A. retinoides and A neriifolia really identical. The first I know as a wild plant since 1847. It is a more southern species than A Neriifolia and it is <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">[ever]flowering</hi>
               </seg>, the only Acacia which has that character as far as I am aware in Australia. The differences, pointed out by Bentham,<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bentham (1863-78), vol. 2, p. 363.</p>
               </note> hold probably good; but in herbaria easily confusion may arise between the two, particularly from mere flowering specimens. I found the f[unicle]<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Partly obscured by binding.</p>
               </note> one of the best distinctions in Acacia. I will reexamine my now much increased Material here.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Always regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Acacia%20neriifolia">Acacia neriifolia</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Acacia%20retinoides">Acacia retinoides</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Acacia%20tortilis">Acacia tortilis</name>
            </p>
